attributes.magic: PE32+ executable (GUI) x86-64, for MS Windows

threat_severity.level_description: Severity MEDIUM because it was considered trojan.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a sophisticated backdoor or Command and Control (C2) agent, likely a variant of a known offensive framework (such as Sliver or a custom implant) that utilizes Slack for communication. It exhibits several high-confidence malicious behaviors: 1) Dynamic API Resolution: It resolves nearly all Windows APIs at runtime using a hash-based lookup (seen in sub_14001604d and sub_1400138bf) to bypass static import analysis. 2) C2 via Slack: The binary contains strings and logic for interacting with 'msdevchat.slack.com', utilizing specific workspace IDs (T58291047) and channel IDs (C83920145) to receive commands and exfiltrate data. 3) Process Injection/Hollowing: Function sub_14000a428 contains logic to target and potentially inject code into legitimate system processes like 'Werfault.exe'. 4) Modular Dispatcher: The sample uses multiple switch-case dispatchers (e.g., sub_140003e74, sub_140002b20) to execute commands including recursive file searching, process management, and cryptographic operations using an AES implementation (sub_14001533a).
